The Most Essential Part of Accessible Interactions

The keyboard is one of the most essential testing tools that we have. It is also the most essential part of accessible interactions.

The first thing I do when I’m testing any website or web application is to start hitting the Tab key to make sure that the various controls on a page are reachable and operable with the keyboard.

Examining Controls on the CampSpots Homepage

A quick way to determine if a control is reachable is to look for a visible focus outline.

The first time you hit Tab on the CampSpots demo app homepage, you’ll see a blue focus outline (in most browsers) around the logo for the site that links us to the homepage.

We are able to Tab through the various MegaNav buttons, opening them with the Enter key or Space bar. We can also Tab through the submenu items when a submenu is open and hit Escape to close the MegaNav.

This is all thanks to the work we did previously, where we changed divs into buttons and added some JavaScript.

Further down the page, we are able to Tab over to the search button. It does show a visible focus outline but the default blue on black is harder to see.

Although the focus contrast of the button isn’t great, we at least know that we are able to reach it with the keyboard.

Before we fixed them in a prior workshop, both the MegaNav buttons and the search buttons were originally divs with JavaScript click event handlers added to them. Switching to button elements made them focusable and operable for free.

In this section, we’ll dive deeper into patterns, conventions, and techniques of how to make things respond to the keyboard.

Examining Controls on the Listings Page

Navigating over to the Listings page, we’ll start hitting Tab again.

The MegaNav options are reachable but then focus jumps from the “Login” link in the menu bar down to the first listing item for Cranberry Lake.

There’s a dropdown component for site types at the top of the page that is skipped over!

If someone visited this page who couldn’t use a mouse (or a screen reader, for that matter), they would not be able to interact with this dropdown.

I see this kind of thing often. Some components have accessibility built-in and others are missed for whatever reason.

This highlights a gap in the testing workflow of the team and shows that they aren’t testing with a keyboard.

Inspecting the Dropdown Markup

Using DevTools, inspect the markup for the dropdown to find out what the issue is.

You guessed it—it’s a div!

Watch how DevTools updates when you open and close the dropdown menu. When it’s open, an active CSS class is added and then the list of links is rendered.

Links are focusable when they are rendered but this only happens when the dropdown is open. This aspect is good for a keyboard user since it doesn’t force them to cycle through things a visual mouse user could skip visually. We looked at a similar issue in the work we did on the MegaNav submenu items in the Manual Testing workshop.

We’ll talk more about rendering, display, and visibility and how they affect keyboard & screen reader access later on.

Examining the Listing Items

The Listing items are focusable and operable. There are even tooltips on the amenity icons.

Tooltips can be a polarizing topic in web development. There is some work we could do on these, but that’s a topic for a later time.

Examining the Date Picker on a Listing Detail Page

Each of the Listing Detail pages includes a custom date picker component.

There are reachable button elements at the top to choose the active month. Each of the individual dates also uses a button so they are reachable as well.

It’s good that we can reach each date but the experience of using the date picker as a whole could be much more ergonomic.

Later we will work on a more intentional date picker design that will allow it to be operated as a single group and used more like a joystick.
